I agree with Melissa's thinking. I have a couple of females who can be just
as nasty or more nasty than my males. I generally have peace in the 55 gal
community tank where they are because I have a lot of places for them to
hide.

Also, when you added the females to the main tank you gave them the chance
to change the 'seniority' among them. A change of environment may have made
a shy one braver and a bully scared in the bigger tank.

You'll also find that many people who have Betta's think it's a very bad
idea to keep males and females together. It's very unlikely they'll live
peacefully. It's also very unlikely a mating would be able to occur with
other fish around and all of the motion in a big tank. In the wild Betta's
tend to be solitary fish and even 'tho the Betta's sold now aren't likely to
be wild caught, they haven't lost the part of them that makes them this way.

Donna

