My first guess is that it is the female Bettas that have attacked the
male (although there may be other fin nippers in your tank) -
especially if they weren't ready to mate and he was......another
consideration is that one of your females might actually be a male.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;From what I've heard you can have mixed results adding females in with
">

a male as a permanent arrangement (Tynk where are you as you could
best answer this?)......you should always have a back up plan when
adding bettas into the same tank as you just don't know which way it
will go. You don't say how large the tank is - even mixing a group of
females can be a problem in a smaller tank although it depends on the
actual fish you buy.......I had 3 females in a 135g tank and one of
them got picked off by the other two girls but this was while we were
on holiday so I wasn't able to observe the behaviour and rescue the
subordinate fish....the remaining two do squabble but there is enough
room for them to run off and hide if it all gets a bit too much....in
a smaller tank they don't have this option......

If you can, I would remove either the females or the male. Even if you
remove the male temporarily this will give him a chance to
recover.....watch out for any infections.....clean water (ie. lots of
water changes) will aid his recovery and help prevent infection/fungal
growth - you might consider adding Pimafix/Melafix as a preventitive
measure or as a curative measure if he is already infected.....

I would doubt that the betta has injured himself on the plastic plants
unless they are very sharp, in which case they probably shouldn't be
in the tank anyway.......Bettas do not have the common name of Siamese
Fighting Fish for nothing.....

Gill
